# Fraction Magnitude Thinking

Common misconceptions:

children may believe:

```text id="p4f1qe"
larger denominator
=
larger fraction
```

or:

```text id="u9f6qe"
larger numerator
always
means larger fraction
```

Some may think:

```text id="c3f8qe"
1/8
>
1/4
```

because:

```text id="k8f5qe"
8
>
4
```

without understanding:

```text id="n1f7qe"
more pieces
means
smaller pieces
```

Students may also think:

```text id="t5f3qe"
2/4
and
1/2
```

are:

```text id="q2f9qe"
different amounts
```

instead of recognizing:

```text id="v4f6qe"
equivalent fractions
represent
same quantity
```

This skill teaches:

```text id="a6f8qe"
fraction magnitude reasoning
```

For Grade 5:

focus includes:

Fraction Equivalence:

* equivalent fractions
* simplifying
* scaling numerators
* scaling denominators
* visual models

Comparison:

* benchmark fractions
* common denominators
* number lines
* reasoning strategies
* magnitude comparisons

Important idea:

```text id="g1f4rx"
fractions
represent
quantities
```

